# Top-level Caddy config for little-living-apps — auto-HTTPS (Let's Encrypt) reverse proxy.
#
# This file holds NO site of its own. Every app is published the same way: each instance — the
# primary AND each bin/new-instance app — drops its own site block at /etc/caddy/sites/<name>.caddy
# (written by bin/lib-caddy.sh), imported below. That keeps n=1 and n>1 identical and lets the top
# file be regenerated without ever clobbering an instance. A glob that matches nothing is fine —
# Caddy just serves nothing until an instance is published.
#
# Publishing is automatic: set LILA_DOMAIN when you run bootstrap.sh (primary) or bin/new-instance
# (additional apps) and the site block + the caddy package are installed for you. The bot itself
# needs none of this — it reaches Telegram outbound — so Caddy is only ever about exposing an app.
#
# Access control is the app's job: Rails' built-in auth (bin/rails generate authentication) gates who
# gets in. Caddy just publishes and terminates TLS; it does not authenticate.
import /etc/caddy/sites/*.caddy
